{"key":"post-15440171","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>15440171</id>\n<content>Usually, aborts are soft and tear right off without damaging the substrate.&amp;nbsp; If they're firmly attached, they're probably not aborts but rather pins for a future flush sitting dormant.&amp;nbsp; If in doubt, cut them with a knife or scissors.&amp;nbsp; Don't damage the substrate.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I have read its best to pull your aborts asap, for it could mould and contaminate your cake. But if its mycelium could it do that? &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;That's more disinformation which keeps getting repeated.&amp;nbsp; Aborts will never 'rot', especially in the time it takes for the rest of the flush to finish.&amp;nbsp; Pick them off when you harvest the rest.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>15440177</next>\n<prev>15440017</prev>\n<first>15440017</first>\n<last>15440177</last>\n<when>1322597845</when>\n<utime>11/29/11 10:17 PM</utime>\n</post>"}